The canonical interval greedy. Once intervals are sorted by start, any overlap must involve the **most recently placed** interval in the result — so you only ever compare against `res.back()`.

[[fig:m14-merge-timeline]]

```cpp
// Merge overlapping intervals. Canonical interval greedy.
vector<vector<int>> merge(vector<vector<int>>& iv) {
    sort(iv.begin(), iv.end());          // sort by START
    vector<vector<int>> res;
    for (auto& x : iv) {
        // If res empty OR current start is beyond last end -> no overlap, push new.
        if (res.empty() || x[0] > res.back()[1]) {
            res.push_back(x);
        } else {
            // Overlap: extend the last interval's end to the max.
            res.back()[1] = max(res.back()[1], x[1]);
        }
    }
    return res;
}
```

The carried value here is `res.back()[1]` — the end of the interval you're currently growing. Each new interval either overlaps it (extend the end with `max`) or starts a fresh one.

> [!EXAMPLE]
> `[[1,4],[3,6],[8,10]]` (already sorted). Take `[1,4]`. Next `[3,6]`: is `3 > 4`? No — overlap, extend end to `max(4,6) = 6`, giving `[1,6]`. Next `[8,10]`: is `8 > 6`? Yes — push new. Result: `[[1,6],[8,10]]`.

> [!PITFALL]
> Why `max(res.back()[1], x[1])` and not just `x[1]`? Because a later interval can be *nested*: after `[1,10]`, the interval `[2,3]` overlaps but must **not** shrink your end to 3. Forgetting the `max` is the classic merge bug.

> [!PITFALL]
> Guard the empty case: `res.empty() ||` must come first in the condition, or `res.back()` on an empty vector is undefined behavior. And if the input itself can be empty, returning the empty list is the sane base case.

Different question, different sort key. Now you want the **maximum number of non-overlapping intervals** (equivalently: minimum removals, or fewest arrows to hit every balloon). The winning move: sort by **end time** and always take the interval that finishes earliest among those still compatible.

[[fig:m14-sort-by-end]]

```cpp
// Pick the MOST non-overlapping intervals. Key: sort by END, not start.
int maxNonOverlap(vector<vector<int>>& iv) {
    sort(iv.begin(), iv.end(),
         [](auto& a, auto& b){ return a[1] < b[1]; }); // earliest finish first
    int count = 0, lastEnd = INT_MIN;
    for (auto& x : iv) {
        if (x[0] >= lastEnd) {   // starts after (or when) last chosen ends
            count++;
            lastEnd = x[1];      // commit to this interval
        }
    }
    return count;               // removals = total - count
}
```

Why end and not start? Finishing earliest **leaves the most room** for everything after it — that's the exchange argument made physical. Sorting by start fails hard: a long early interval hogs the timeline and blocks several short ones you should have kept.

> [!KEY]
> Two questions, two sort keys. **Merging** intervals → sort by *start* (overlaps must be adjacent). **Selecting the most** intervals → sort by *end* (earliest finish frees the most room). Say the key out loud before you type a character.

> [!EXAM]
> Three OA problems are this exact template wearing costumes: *Non-overlapping Intervals* asks for `n - count` (removals), *Arrows* asks how many committed ends you needed (touching counts as overlap — use strict `>`), and *max meetings you can attend* asks for `count` itself. Recognize the costume, reuse the scan.

The jump-game family. No sorting here — the array order *is* the timeline. The carried value is `farthest`: the rightmost index you could possibly reach with everything seen so far.

```cpp
// Can you reach the last index? Track the FARTHEST reachable so far.
bool canJump(vector<int>& nums) {
    int farthest = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) {
        if (i > farthest) return false;          // stuck: can't even reach i
        farthest = max(farthest, i + nums[i]);   // greedily extend reach
    }
    return true;
}
```

Two things make this correct:

1. **If `i > farthest`, you're stranded.** Index `i` is beyond everything reachable, and it can never improve — no future cell helps because you can't get to any future cell.
2. **`farthest` only needs one value.** You don't care *which* index gets you far, only how far you can get. Collapsing "the set of reachable indices" into a single frontier number is what makes this $O(n)$ instead of a graph search.

[[fig:m14-jump-levels]]

The follow-up, *minimum* number of jumps, keeps the same `farthest` idea but adds level boundaries — it's a BFS where you never build the queue (full walkthrough in the deep dives).

> [!INTUITION]
> Picture a wave front sweeping right. Each index you visit pushes the frontier out by `i + nums[i]`. You only fail if the scan pointer catches up to a frozen frontier.

> [!PITFALL]
> On adversarial constraints, `i + nums[i]` (and gas-station sums) can overflow `int`. Your CP habit of reaching for `long long` when values approach $10^9$ is correct — keep it.

deepdives.answer:
**Why one `lastEnd` isn't enough.** Unlike scheduling, several meetings can be simultaneously live, and a room frees up only when *its own* meeting ends. At each new start you need to know whether **any** room has freed — that's a set of end times, not a single value.

**Trick A — min-heap of end times.** Sort by start. The heap holds the end times of currently occupied rooms; the top is always the room that frees *soonest*. For each meeting: if the top is ≤ this start, pop (reuse that room); then push this meeting's end. The final heap size is the answer, because you only ever grew the heap when no room was free.

```cpp
int minMeetingRooms(vector<vector<int>>& m) {
    sort(m.begin(), m.end());                 // by start
    priority_queue<int, vector<int>, greater<int>> pq; // min-heap of end times
    for (auto& x : m) {
        if (!pq.empty() && pq.top() <= x[0]) pq.pop(); // a room freed up
        pq.push(x[1]);
    }
    return pq.size();
}
```

> [!NOTE]
> This is deliberately also your **heaps rep** — `priority_queue` with `greater<int>` is a gap for you, and this is the cleanest place to make it muscle memory: min-heap = "give me the room that frees first."

**Trick B — sweep line / event counting (slicker, right in your prefix-sum wheelhouse).** Forget assigning rooms entirely. Every meeting is two events: `+1` at its start, `−1` at its end. Sort the starts and ends separately and sweep: before admitting each start, retire every end that's ≤ it; the peak of the running counter is the answer.

[[fig:m14-sweep-line]]

```cpp
int minMeetingRooms(vector<vector<int>>& m) {
    vector<int> starts, ends;
    for (auto& x : m){ starts.push_back(x[0]); ends.push_back(x[1]); }
    sort(starts.begin(), starts.end());
    sort(ends.begin(), ends.end());
    int rooms = 0, best = 0, j = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < starts.size(); i++) {
        while (j < ends.size() && ends[j] <= starts[i]) { rooms--; j++; }
        rooms++;
        best = max(best, rooms);
    }
    return best;
}
```

Note `ends[j] <= starts[i]`: a meeting ending exactly when another begins hands over its room (typical for this problem — but confirm against the examples).

**Complexity:** both tricks are $O(n \log n)$ time, $O(n)$ space.

**What generalizes:** "max concurrent anything" — CPU jobs, bandwidth, platform trains — is the same +1/−1 sweep. It's a prefix-sum over events, which is exactly the CP tool you already own.

**Why naive fails.** The obvious DP — `dp[i]` = min jumps to reach `i`, relaxing every predecessor — is $O(n^2)$ and TLEs on big OA inputs. The greedy is $O(n)$, and the way to *see* it is as a BFS you never build.

> [!INTUITION] Levels without a queue
> Everything reachable in 1 jump is "level 1", in 2 jumps "level 2", and so on. The current level is just a window `[.. curEnd]`. While scanning it you compute `farthest` — the boundary of the *next* level. When `i` hits `curEnd`, the level is exhausted: increment `jumps`, slide the boundary to `farthest`.

[[fig:m14-jump-levels]]

```cpp
int jump(vector<int>& nums) {
    int jumps = 0, curEnd = 0, farthest = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i + 1 < nums.size(); i++) {  // no need to jump FROM the last index
        farthest = max(farthest, i + nums[i]);   // best reach discovered this level
        if (i == curEnd) {                       // exhausted current jump's range
            jumps++;
            curEnd = farthest;                   // next level's right boundary
        }
    }
    return jumps;
}
```

**Trace on `[2,3,1,1,4]`:** `i=0`: farthest = 2; `i == curEnd(0)` → jumps = 1, curEnd = 2. `i=1`: farthest = max(2, 4) = 4. `i=2`: `i == curEnd` → jumps = 2, curEnd = 4. Loop ends before the last index. Answer **2** — exactly the two BFS levels in the figure.

> [!PITFALL]
> The `i + 1 < nums.size()` guard is the whole correctness subtlety: if you loop to the last index, landing exactly on it triggers one final `i == curEnd` and you over-count by one jump. You never need to jump *from* the destination.

**Complexity:** $O(n)$ time, $O(1)$ space.

**What generalizes:** whenever "minimum steps" lives on a line and each position reaches a contiguous range, you can run BFS with two integers (`curEnd`, `farthest`) instead of a queue. That reframing — *greedy as compressed BFS* — is worth remembering on its own.

**Why naive fails.** Simulating the loop from every start is $O(n^2)$. The one-pass greedy rests on two lemmas that are genuinely non-obvious — this is a *prove it or don't trust it* problem.

**Lemma 1 (feasibility).** If total gas < total cost, no start works — return `-1`. (Fuel is conserved; the loop's net balance doesn't depend on where you start.)

**Lemma 2 (the jump).** If a solution exists, then whenever the running tank goes negative arriving at station `i`, **no station in `start..i` can be the answer** — the next candidate is `i+1`.

> [!INTUITION] Why lemma 2 holds
> You arrived at every intermediate station `k` in `start..i` with tank ≥ 0. Starting *at* `k` instead means arriving at `i` with that cushion removed — even less fuel. If the trip failed with a head start, it fails without one. So the entire failed prefix is disqualified at once, and the scan never re-visits it — that's what makes one pass enough.

[[fig:m14-gas-tank]]

```cpp
int canCompleteCircuit(vector<int>& gas, vector<int>& cost) {
    int total = 0, tank = 0, start = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < gas.size(); i++) {
        int diff = gas[i] - cost[i];
        total += diff;
        tank  += diff;
        if (tank < 0) { start = i + 1; tank = 0; } // can't start in [old start..i]
    }
    return total >= 0 ? start : -1;
}
```

**Trace (`diff = [-2,-2,-2,+3,+3]`):** tank goes negative at stations 0, 1, 2 — each failure jumps `start` forward. From `start = 3` the tank stays ≥ 0, and `total = 0 ≥ 0` confirms feasibility, so the answer is 3.

The elegance: **one pass computes both** the feasibility check (`total`) and the answer (`start`). Note `start` is never wrapped around — lemma 1 guarantees that if `total ≥ 0`, the final candidate survives the wrap.

**Complexity:** $O(n)$ time, $O(1)$ space. Use `long long` for the sums if constraints are large.

**What generalizes:** the "failed prefix disqualifies every start inside it" argument reappears in maximum-subarray-flavored problems (it's Kadane's reset in disguise) — when a running sum going negative kills all prefixes, reset and move on.
